column8: P1. Leave the policy settings as they are.
column9: P2. Policies that emphasise fewer regulations (e.g., policies that promote free trade agreements by reducing food regulation)
column10: P3. Policies that involve a moderate sustainable regulations (e.g., banning certain types of pesticides, incentivising organic agriculture)
column11: P4. Policies that involve a radical sustainable food regulation (e.g., banning all pesticides, banning the importation of food related product that employ non-sustanable approaches, exclusively incentivising organic agriculture)
column12: P5. Policies that create incentives for local producers to produce sustainable food (e.g., subsidies or tax breaks for local farmers who produce organic products)
column13: P6. Adaptation policies and expenditure. Planning controls and emergency response programs.
column14: P7. Preparing for climate risk for food production through the development of new approaches and technologies that enhance resilience to the impacts of climate variability or change.
